        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is AI-native marketing?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "AI-native marketing means building your marketing system around AI from the ground up — not adding AI tools to an existing process. The difference: a bolt-on approach uses AI to speed up existing tasks (generating copy faster, auto-scheduling posts). An AI-native approach redesigns the workflow so that AI handles the repetitive, scalable work while the human focuses on strategy, relationships, and creative judgment.",
          },
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why are DACH SMEs behind on AI marketing adoption?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Three structural reasons: First, the dominant AI marketing tools are English-language and US-centric — they don't understand German phrasing, DACH buying behaviour, or local compliance requirements like GDPR and UWG. Second, DACH SMEs typically don't have a dedicated marketing team; the owner or one generalist handles everything, leaving no capacity to evaluate and implement new tools. Third, the ROI case for AI marketing is usually made with US startup metrics that don't translate to a Mittelstand context.",
          },
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Which AI marketing tools are best for German SMEs?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The right answer depends on where you are in your marketing maturity. For SMEs just starting: a structured approach to content creation using LLM assistants (Claude, GPT-4) with German-language prompts will give you the fastest ROI. For SMEs with an existing digital presence: AI-assisted campaign analysis (spotting what's working across channels) and automated audience segmentation produce measurable results within 60 days. The key is not which tool — it is building the workflow that makes the tool produce consistent output without requiring daily attention.",
          },
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What marketing results can a DACH SME realistically achieve with AI?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Based on enterprise-scale implementations: a unified content production system can reduce production costs by 30-50% while increasing output volume. A purchase-intent content strategy — content designed to appear when prospects are actively researching — generated €M+ in annual organic media value at BSH within 6–12 months. The honest caveat: these results come from systematic implementation, not from subscribing to a tool. The tool is 20% of the result; the workflow is 80%.",
          },
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is AI marketing compliant with GDPR in Germany?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "AI marketing itself is GDPR-compliant when implemented correctly. The key compliance considerations: consent for personalisation (any AI-driven personalisation using personal data requires explicit consent), transparency requirements (automated decision-making that affects individuals requires disclosure), and data minimisation (AI tools should only process the personal data necessary for the specific marketing function). Working with German-based or EU-based AI marketing tools reduces compliance overhead significantly.",
          },
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How long does it take to implement AI marketing for a DACH SME?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Phase 1 (content production system) takes 4–6 weeks and delivers measurable time savings immediately. Phase 2 (purchase-intent content) builds over 2–6 months; organic traffic typically starts within 90 days of the first published pieces, with significant volume by month six. Phase 3 (analytics loop) takes one month to set up and then runs as a weekly 30-minute process. Full implementation across all three phases is a 6–9 month project for most DACH SMEs.",
          },
